Multimedia Elements
•	Make the webpage visually appealing.
•	Help users understand content quickly through images or videos.
•	Provide demonstrations or tutorials better than text.
•	Improve accessibility (audio for visually impaired users).
•	Attract and hold user attention.

Code:
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Sample Image">
<audio controls src="audio.mp3"></audio>
<video controls src="video.mp4"></video>
Hyperlinks
•	Connect users to related information easily.
•	Improve website navigation.
•	Reduce text clutter by linking instead of writing long explanations.
•	Allow users to jump within the same page (anchor links).
•	Provide quick access to external resources.

Code:
<a href="https://example.com">Visit Website</a>
Tables
•	Organize information in rows and columns.
•	Make data easy to compare side by side.
•	Improve readability of structured information.
•	Help present large data clearly (pricing, schedules).
•	Allow users to scan information quickly.

Code:
<table border="1">
  <tr><th>Name</th><th>Age</th></tr>
  <tr><td>John</td><td>25</td></tr>
</table>
Forms
•	Allow users to enter information (login, sign-up, feedback).
•	Enable communication between users and website.
•	Help collect data efficiently.
•	Improve interaction and user engagement.
•	Make the website functional (search bars, contact forms).

Code:
<form>
  <input type="text" placeholder="Enter Name">
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
Lists
•	Present information in a clean and organized way.
•	Help users read and understand quickly.
•	Highlight key points without long paragraphs.
•	Ordered lists show steps or rankings clearly.
•	Unordered lists display features, menus, or points neatly.

Code:
<ul>
  <li>Item 1</li>
  <li>Item 2</li>
</ul>

<ol>
  <li>Step 1</li>
  <li>Step 2</li>
</ol>
